SkyScrub AeroClean V1

Type: robotic | Generated: 12/6/2025

Executive Summary

A specialized autonomous quadcopter designed for high-altitude window cleaning on skyscrapers. The system utilizes active vacuum adhesion to cling to vertical glass surfaces, allowing a robotic manipulator to wash and squeegee windows while minimizing energy consumption compared to constant hovering. It is engineered with high-torque propulsion to stabilize against strong wind gusts typical at high elevations.

Generated Implementation (cpp)

#include 

// Pin Definitions
const int PIN_VACUUM_ESC = 9;       // PWM control for Vacuum Impeller
const int PIN_PRESSURE_SENS = A0;   // Analog input from vacuum pressure sensor
const int PIN_TETHER_LOCK = 4;      // Solenoid for tether management
const int PIN_PROXIMITY = 5;        // ToF sensor interrupt

// Constants
const float TARGET_VACUUM_KPA = -25.0; // Target suction pressure
const float CRITICAL_VACUUM_KPA = -15.0; // Safety threshold

// State Machine
enum DroneState {
  STATE_HOVER,
  STATE_APPROACH,
  STATE_ADHERED,
  STATE_CLEANING,
  STATE_EMERGENCY_RECOVERY
};

DroneState currentState = STATE_HOVER;
float currentPressureKpa = 0.0;

// Mock function to read calibrated sensor data
float readPressure() {
  int raw = analogRead(PIN_PRESSURE_SENS);
  // Convert raw 0-1023 to KPa (0 to -100)
  return map(raw, 0, 1023, 0, -100);
}

// PID-like control for Vacuum Motor to save energy vs holding max throttle
void maintainAdhesion(float currentP) {
  if (currentP > TARGET_VACUUM_KPA) {
    // Pressure is too high (weak suction), increase motor speed
    analogWrite(PIN_VACUUM_ESC, 220); // High power
  } else {
    // Pressure is good, maintain lower holding power to save battery
    analogWrite(PIN_VACUUM_ESC, 150); // Efficient holding power
  }
}

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(115200);
  pinMode(PIN_VACUUM_ESC, OUTPUT);
  pinMode(PIN_TETHER_LOCK, OUTPUT);
  
  // Initialize ESC
  analogWrite(PIN_VACUUM_ESC, 0);
  digitalWrite(PIN_TETHER_LOCK, HIGH); // Engage safety tether lock
}

void loop() {
  currentPressureKpa = readPressure();

  switch (currentState) {
    case STATE_HOVER:
      // Flight controller handles position. Waiting for command.
      // Logic to switch to APPROACH based on RF command omitted.
      break;

    case STATE_APPROACH:
      // Move towards glass using flight motors.
      // If proximity sensor triggers contact:
      analogWrite(PIN_VACUUM_ESC, 255); // Max suction for initial grab
      if (currentPressureKpa <= TARGET_VACUUM_KPA) {
        currentState = STATE_ADHERED;
        Serial.println("Surface Adhered. Stabilizing.");
      }
      break;

    case STATE_ADHERED:
      // Confirm stability before cleaning
      maintainAdhesion(currentPressureKpa);
      currentState = STATE_CLEANING;
      break;

    case STATE_CLEANING:
      maintainAdhesion(currentPressureKpa);
      
      // Safety Check: If wind gust breaks seal
      if (currentPressureKpa > CRITICAL_VACUUM_KPA) {
        Serial.println("CRITICAL: Suction Loss Detected!");
        analogWrite(PIN_VACUUM_ESC, 255); // Panic Boost
        if (currentPressureKpa > CRITICAL_VACUUM_KPA + 5.0) {
            // If still failing, abort to flight mode
            currentState = STATE_EMERGENCY_RECOVERY;
        }
      } else {
         // Run Manipulator Logic (e.g., servo wipes)
         // runWiperMechanism();
      }
      break;

    case STATE_EMERGENCY_RECOVERY:
      // Disengage cleaning arms, prepare for free flight
      analogWrite(PIN_VACUUM_ESC, 0);
      // Flight controller takes over to stabilize against wind
      // Log event to black box
      break;
  }

  delay(20); // Control loop freq ~50Hz
}

Validation Checks

  • Contradiction in Propulsion Specs: The Summary and Key Requirements call for 'high-torque propulsion' for wind stabilization, but the Parts List specifies 'High-KV brushless motors'. High-KV motors typically produce low torque and are designed for speed/racing; a heavy-lift drone carrying 5kg+ needs Low-KV motors to swing larger propellers efficiently.
  • Physical Conflict in Geometry/Arm Placement: The 'Active Suction Pods' are located on the 'underside of the frame legs', and the 'Cleaning Manipulator Arm' is on the 'underside front chassis'. If the drone attaches belly-to-wall (underside touching glass), the cleaning arm would be sandwiched between the drone body and the glass, unable to move unless it has a specific cutout or extends significantly beyond the suction plane.
  • Battery Capacity vs. Duration: A 5000mAh 6S battery is insufficient to power a 5kg drone + vacuum pump + manipulator arm for 25 minutes. A drone of this weight class typically achieves 10-12 minutes on such a battery. The requirement should either lower the duration or significantly increase battery capacity (e.g., 10,000mAh+), which would further impact the weight limit.
  • Gravity/Peel Physics: The diagram depicts the drone in a standard X-frame configuration attached vertically to a wall. If the motors 'throttle down to idle' (as stated in Interactions), the center of mass (hanging outward from the wall) creates a massive moment arm, likely peeling the top suction cups off the glass. The design requires a low-profile frame or a gimbaled suction mount to keep the Center of Mass (CoM) close to the surface.
  • Fluid System Orientation: The fluid reservoir is described as a 'central tank', but for a drone rotating 90 degrees to clean, a standard rigid tank may cause air intake issues (cavitation) when the fluid level drops. It requires a bladder or pressurized system to function in both horizontal flight and vertical cleaning orientations.
